{"title_page": "Rebecca Morse (ice hockey)", "text_new": "{{short description|American ice hockey forward}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1992|3|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Westfield]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 173\n| weight_lb = \n| position = [[Defence (ice hockey)]]\n| shoots = Left\n| team = [[Metropolitan Riveters]]\n| league = [[NWHL]]\n| played_for = [[Providence College]]\n| ntl_team = \n| draft = \n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| career_start = 2016\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Morse''' is an American [[ice hockey]] defender, currently playing for the [[Metropolitan Riveters]] of the [[NWHL]].\n\n== Career ==\n\nAs a freshman for Providence College, Morse was named to the Hockey East All-Rookie Team. She went on to score 60 points across 136 games for Providence.<ref>https://thehockeywriters.com/q-a-with-rebecca-morse-of-the-new-york-riveters/</ref> After graduating, she took a few years off hockey, before returning to sign with the New York Riveters of the NWHL in 2016.\n\nIn 2018, she won the [[Isobel Cup]] with the Riveters. In 2019, she was named an alternate captain for the Riveters.<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/11/22/20966124/rebecca-morse-made-a-statement-with-her-play-in-october-metropolitan-riveters-nwhl-womens-hockey</ref> In 2020, her fourth season in the NWHL, Morse was named to the All-Star Game for the first time, with a career-high 11 points in 24 games, and was honoured with the NWHL Foundation Award.<ref>https://thehockeywriters.com/metropolitan-riveters-rebecca-morse-fifth-season/</ref><ref>https://www.nwhl.zone/news/nwhl-foundation-award-winners-2019-20-season</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nMorse has been nicknamed \"The Moose,\" and grew up in New Jersey.<ref>https://mycentraljersey.com/story/sports/2018/03/02/westfields-rebecca-morse-thriving-national-womens-hockey-league/379192002/</ref><ref>https://www.nhl.com/video/nhl-now-rebecca-morse/t-282785066/c-53947203</ref> She has an MBA from Providence College, and in 2015 was a communications intern for the [[New Jersey Devils]].\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from Elite Prospects<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/493744/rebecca-morse |website=Elite Propsects}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Metropolitan Riveters players]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people]]\n[[Category:American ice hockey players]]\n\n\n{{US-icehockey-player-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American ice hockey forward}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1992|3|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Westfield]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 173\n| weight_lb = \n| position = [[Defence (ice hockey)]]\n| shoots = Left\n| team = [[Metropolitan Riveters]]\n| league = [[NWHL]]\n| played_for = [[Providence College]]\n| ntl_team = \n| draft = \n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| career_start = 2016\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Morse''' is an American [[ice hockey]] defender, currently playing for the [[Metropolitan Riveters]] of the [[NWHL]]. \n\n== Career == \n\nAs a freshman for Providence College, Morse was named to the Hockey East All-Rookie Team. She went on to score 60 points across 136 games for Providence.<ref>https://thehockeywriters.com/q-a-with-rebecca-morse-of-the-new-york-riveters/</ref> After graduating, she took a few years off hockey, before returning to sign with the New York Riveters of the NWHL in 2016.\n\nIn 2018, she won the [[Isobel Cup]] with the Riveters. In 2019, she was named an alternate captain for the Riveters.<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/11/22/20966124/rebecca-morse-made-a-statement-with-her-play-in-october-metropolitan-riveters-nwhl-womens-hockey</ref> In 2020, her fourth season in the NWHL, Morse was named to the All-Star Game for the first time, with a career-high 11 points in 24 games, and was honoured with the NWHL Foundation Award.<ref>https://thehockeywriters.com/metropolitan-riveters-rebecca-morse-fifth-season/</ref><ref>https://www.nwhl.zone/news/nwhl-foundation-award-winners-2019-20-season</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==   \n\nMorse has been nicknamed \"The Moose,\" and grew up in New Jersey.<ref>https://mycentraljersey.com/story/sports/2018/03/02/westfields-rebecca-morse-thriving-national-womens-hockey-league/379192002/</ref><ref>https://www.nhl.com/video/nhl-now-rebecca-morse/t-282785066/c-53947203</ref> She has an MBA from Providence College, and in 2015 was a communications intern for the [[New Jersey Devils]].\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from Elite Prospects<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/493744/rebecca-morse |website=Elite Propsects}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Metropolitan Riveters players]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people]]\n[[Category:American ice hockey players]]\n\n{{US-icehockey-player-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_Morse_(ice_hockey)"}
{"title_page": "Elastic Path", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=September 2019}}\n{{Prose|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Elastic Path\n[[File:Elastic-path-software-inc-vector-logo-2019.svg|thumb|Elastic Path Software Vector Logo]]\n| founders            = Harry Chemko, Mark Williams, Ryan Orr, Jason Billingsley\n| area_served         = Global\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list|[[Harry Chemko]] ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])|[[Sal Visca]] ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])| Darin Archer ([[Chief strategy officer|CSO]]) |Brenton Brown ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])|John Bruno ([[Vice President of Product Management]])}}\n| industry            = Ecommerce\n| products            = Enterprise Ecommerce Software\n| foundation          = 2000\n| location_country    = [[Canada]], [[United States]], [[UK]],\n| homepage            = http://www.elasticpath.com\n}}\nAs the pioneer of headless commerce, Elastic Path empowers organizations to create unified commerce experiences across channels, devices and business models on a single platform. Specifically focused on serving the commerce needs of enterprise organizations, Elastic Path is known for revolutionizing commerce by pushing the industry forward and always existing on the leading edge of commerce technology innovation.\n\n== History ==\nElastic Path was started by Harry Chemko in 2000, with co-founders Mark Williams, Ryan Orr, and Jason Billingsley, after completing university with a $15,000 start-up loan from a non-profit organization. Based on the idea that there had to be a better way to build enterprise software, they had a vision for solutions that were simpler, intelligently architected and provided ultimate flexibility.\n\nDuring the 2010 Vancouver Olympics, Elastic Path signed on to power the tech behind the official Olympics online store. They experienced the pain points first-hand of the modern retailer when it came to things like huge surges in volume, extensive product catalogues and accommodating shoppers from all over the world. Additionally, it became clear to CEO Harry Chemko that the proliferation of digital experience channels would only accelerate, creating an opportunity for brands to commerce-enable all new and emerging customer touchpoints.\n\nAs a result, Elastic Path built the first API centric commerce platform, incorporating \u201cshopping APIs\u201d to create a purchase experience within any device or touchpoint, calling this concept \u201cheadless commerce.\u201d\n\nIn 2013, Elastic Path launched [https://vimeo.com/70425078 Cortex]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/70425078|title=Cortex - A revolutionary way to build your digital empire|last=Chemko|first=Harry|date=2013|website=Vimeo|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>, completely decoupling digital experiences from the back-end system while providing a layer of commerce business logic. This release was revolutionary because it made the creation of innovative commerce experiences accessible to business and marketing users without having to rely on IT teams.\n\nThis first of its kind release could mediate resources from multiple systems and allow them to be added, removed or upgraded without effecting the customer experience. More importantly, it supported continuous customer journeys across multiple touchpoints and, quick on-boarding of new touchpoints and capabilities.\n\nIn 2019, Elastic Path rebranded and announced their next commerce revolution is in B2B commerce. As an organization, they are committed to powering B2B commerce experiences like IoT purchasing, autonomous machines, manufacturing equipment that can order its own parts and on-site \u201cvending machines\u201d that keep inventory costs low, just to name a few, on a solution that is purpose-built for the way B2B organizations actually operate.\n\nIn 2020, Elastic Path announced the acquisition of commerce technology provider, Moltin<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elasticpath.com/resources/press-releases/ep-acquires-moltin-microservices-powered-agility-in-every-enterprise|title=Elastic Path Acquires Moltin to Create the Only Commerce Solution That Puts Microservices-Powered Digital Innovation Into the Hands of Every Business Leader|website=www.elasticpath.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>. By acquiring Moltin, Elastic Path expanded the capabilities of Elastic Path Commerce Cloud, increasing core flexibility and agility. \n\n== Awards and Milestones ==\n\n=== 2007 ===\nElastic Path won the bid to manage the complete ecommerce operations for the Official Vancouver 2010 Olympic Online Store.<ref>http://www.2010commercecentre.com/BusinessPlanning/SuccessStories/ElasticPath.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614082921/http://www.2010commercecentre.com/BusinessPlanning/SuccessStories/ElasticPath.aspx |date=2011-06-14 }}. Retrieved May 16, 2011</ref>\n\n=== 2008 ===\nElastic Path\u2019s blog, Get Elastic, ranked #1 worldwide ecommerce blog by PostRank<ref>http://adage.com/power150/ AdAge Power 150. Retrieved April 8, 2010</ref> and voted one of the 15 entrepreneur blogs worth reading by the Wall Street Journal.<ref>https://blogs.wsj.com/independentstreet/2008/06/13/15-entrepreneur-blogs-worth-reading/tab/article/. Wall Street Journal. June 13, 2008. Retrieved May 16, 2011</ref>\n\nElastic Path ranked in PROFIT 100 \"Canada's Fastest-growing Companies\" for four consecutive years.<ref>http://www.allbusiness.com/company-activities-management/company-strategy-outsourcing/14575699-1.html. All Business. June 4, 2010. Retrieved May 16, 2011</ref>  The PROFIT 100 profiles the country's most successful growth companies and is Canada's largest annual celebration of entrepreneurial achievement.<ref>http://www.profitguide.com/awards/profit100 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516065614/http://www.profitguide.com/awards/profit100 |date=2011-05-16 }}. Profit 100. Retrieved May 16, 2011</ref>\n\nOpened second office location in Reading, UK.\n\n=== 2010 ===\nElastic Path won BC Export\u2019s Advancing Technologies Award.<ref>http://www.bcexportawards.com/Award_Winners/2010_Winners.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522030552/http://www.bcexportawards.com/Award_Winners/2010_Winners.aspx |date=2011-05-22 }}. Retrieved May 16, 2011</ref>\n\nListed 16th in BCBusiness 2010 Guide to Innovation.<ref>http://www.bcbusinessonline.ca/bcb/tech-innovation/2010/04/02/elastic-path-software {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110106044940/http://www.bcbusinessonline.ca/bcb/tech-innovation/2010/04/02/elastic-path-software |date=2011-01-06 }}. BC Business. April 2, 2010. Retrieved May 16, 2011</ref>\n\nListed #164 in Branham300's Top 250 Canadian Technology Companies.<ref>http://www.branham300.com/index.php?year=2011&listing=1&offset=150. Branham300. Retrieved May 16, 2011</ref>\n\n=== 2013 ===\nElastic Path Raises $8M For Commerce Everywhere API Platform.<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/14/elastic-path-raises-8m-for-commerce-everywhere-api-platform/. Retrieved June 14, 2013</ref>\n\n=== 2014 ===\nElastic Path Teams With Adobe to Release Elastic Path Edition for Adobe Experience Manager.<ref>http://www.prweb.com/releases/adobe-ecommerce-elastic/path-ecommerce-platform/prweb11655046.htm/. Retrieved March 11, 2014</ref><br />\nElastic Path Raises CDN$5.35-Million led by BDC Venture Capital.<ref>http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/elastic-path-raises-cdn535-million-led-by-bdc-venture-capital-274595541.html</ref>\n\n=== 2016 ===\nGartner\u2019s Magic Quadrant for Digital Commerce names Elastic Path as a Visionary in e-commerce applications.<ref>http://www.prweb.com/releases/gartner-magic-quadrant/ecommerce-software/prweb13261888.htm\n\nRetrieved August 22, 2016\n</ref>\n\nElastic Path Announces the Industry\u2019s Most Powerful Enterprise Commerce Cloud.<ref>http://networking.itbusinessnet.com/article/Elastic-Path-Announces-the-Industry---s-Most-Powerful-Enterprise-Commerce-Clo